      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25906621#p25906621" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">CQLanik</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25906601#p25906601" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">flatrock</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The president was talking about the bulk data collection, in which there haven't been found evidence of misuse by NSA employees.  So Loveint is not a direct contradiction of the president's comments.  You could suggest that it is a reason to be concerned, but considering that Loveint disclosed a total of 12 cases over more than 12 years, it wouldn't be the most rational of arguments.  The NSA does hire human beings not perfectly programmed robots that never do anything wrong, but if one incident a year among 10s of thousands of NSA employees, then we should be singing the praises of the incredible level of integrity among NSA employees.<br /><br />They hype I the coverage here on Ars is out of hand, it's gotten to the point of disinformation.</div><br />Well, I can't speak for everyone, but I have considered the possibility that LOVEINT happens more often than once a year, and that the NSA lied in their disclosure.  But then, I have the pattern spotting capabilities of the average chicken, and noticed that the NSA lies at basically every opportunity.</div><br />Even if they didn't lie, how likely is it that we caught 100% of those doing something wrong in an organization based on secrecy?  I'd say it's a big fat zero, as oxymoronic as they my seem.
      
    </div>
