        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/obama-says-snowdens-actions-have-done-unnecessary-damage/?comments=1&post=25906669#comment-25906669" title="2013-12-20T18:08:27-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 6:08 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle">President Obama wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">And just because we can do something doesn’t mean that we necessarily should. And the values that we’ve got as Americans are ones that we have to be willing to apply beyond our borders and perhaps more systematically than we’ve done in the past.”</div><br /><br />I'm taking this out of context, but this right here should be the most important quote for the 21st century.  We have capabilities our forebears never had, and can do things they never could.  But should we be doing it?  That's a question that my country should always be in the process of asking itself, for good reason.<br /><br />More interestingly, though, is the fact that the borders of nations are marginalized by the Internet.  I wonder, how do we solve the can of worms <span style="font-style: italic">that</span> reality opens?
      
    </div>
