<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="9"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="9"
  data-post-id="25907051" data-poster-id="12725" id="comment-25907051">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="fxds"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=12725&amp;sid=d7c57eb09daf12e0d5fa0babe6729c56">fxds</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Tribunus Militum</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/obama-says-snowdens-actions-have-done-unnecessary-damage/?comments=1&post=25907051#comment-25907051" title="2013-12-20T19:48:06-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 7:48 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25906655#p25906655" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Rookie_MIB</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Not to nitpick, but in general, there is no 'right' to 'privacy'.</div><br />That depends on interpretation and where you're standing.  The US Constitution does not explicitly mention a right to privacy, but it was not written as an exhaustive list of rights.  In fact, there was argument over the adoption of The Bill of Rights because some of the founders were concerned that in time it would come to be viewed as a list of all citizen rights, with anything not included not being a right, rather than the non-exhaustive list of examples it was intended to be.  So just because the Constitution doesn't explicitly acknowledge a right to privacy doesn't mean such a right doesn't exist.  An argument could be even be made that privacy is a fundamental component of the inalienable rights of &quot;Life, Liberty, and the pursuit of Happiness&quot; that are explicitly called out in the Declaration of Independence, or of the &quot;Blessings of Liberty&quot; the Constitution states it was in part written to secure.<br /><br />There's also the matter of the Tenth Amendment, which states &quot;The powers not delegated to the United States by the Constitution, nor prohibited by it to the States, are reserved to the States respectively, or to the people.&quot;  Some State Constitutions do explicitly acknowledge a right of privacy, including California, the most populous state in the nation by a rather wide margin, which all by itself represents approximately twelve percent of the US population.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
