<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="16"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="16"
  data-post-id="25907617" data-poster-id="388217" id="comment-25907617">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="TheColinous"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=388217&amp;sid=d7c57eb09daf12e0d5fa0babe6729c56">TheColinous</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/12/obama-says-snowdens-actions-have-done-unnecessary-damage/?comments=1&post=25907617#comment-25907617" title="2013-12-20T22:52:56-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Fri Dec 20, 2013 10:52 pm</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25906345#p25906345" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Korgoth</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Snowden couldn't use proper channels, but I feel he really hurt his cause by running to China, then Russia. If he had given the data over to 4-5 top journalists, then turned himself in, with the press watching, to the FBI, the effect would have been far better for his cause.</div><br /><br />No. If he had done that, we would never know his name. Journalists don't reveal sources. At least, the good ones don't. As soon as Snowden had handed the materials over and reported himself to the police or whatever, he would be whisked to a super-max, and Greenwald and Poitras would never have gotten his permission to reveal himself to the world.<br /><br />There was a value in revealing himself to the world. That removed the deniability of his data trove. If all Greenwald and Poitras had had was the papers, it wouldn't have been nearly as strong as a face that was known to be an NSA contractor sys admin. If al Greenwald and Poitras had had was the data, then the denials would have had much higher credibility.<br /><br />I think we'd still be labelling people that believed the revelations as tin-foil hatted nutters. But he did come forward. He did give his name. He did give a face to the data. And he did remove the deniability from the NSA, which is why they're trashing about now in their web of lies.<br /><br />And remember. Snowden didn't run to Russia. He went to Hong Kong to meet Poitras and Greenwald. Then he flew elsewhere, and while in transit the USA revoked his passport. When he arrived in Russia, he couldn't get on the plane elsewhere. He didn't run to Russia. The USA stranded him in Russia.
      
    </div>
